                  </rs>.</p>
               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182709130146"></xptr>SECOND COUNT, stating then to be the property of 
               <persName id="t18270913-360-victim2599" type="victimName">
                  William Edward 
                  Holderness
               <interp inst="t18270913-360-victim2599" type="surname" value="Holderness"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-360-victim2599" type="given" value="William Edward"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-360-victim2599" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            .</p>
               <p>WILLIAM EDWARD HOLDERNESS, I am a <rs id="t18270913-360-viclabel2001" type="occupation">boot and shoe maker</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18270913-360-victim2599 t18270913-360-viclabel2001"></join>, and live in Barbican. I left this linen in care of my boy on the 25th of July, and he was to deliver it to whoever came to fetch it for Esther Mackenzie; it was for her to wash.</p>
               <p>MARY MORRISH. I am eleven years of age. I received the bundle, and was going to take it to Mrs. Mackenzie, to be washed; she lives at No. 3, Lee's-buildings - when I got to the bottom of Long-lane, Donoghue came and said,"Little girl go over the way, for a halfpenny-worth of tobacco;" he held my bundle, and when I came back he gave me a halfpenny worth of cherries, and gave me the bundle, told me to sit down on a step, and see that it that it was all right - I told him I did not know what was in it. I then went on to the bottom of Long-lane, and he came to me again, and said, "Go over the way, and get two pipes." I left my bundle and went; and when I returned, the prisoner Edwards had run away with it - I asked Donoghue where the bundle was, and he said a boy had run away with it; I had seen Edwards following us before, but not close to us - Donoghue said, "Wait there, and I will run after him." I have not seen the bundle since - I am quite sure it was Donoghue who spoke to me; I did not take particular notice of Edwards, but I believe he is the person.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270913-360-person2600">
                  FRANCIS 
                  GIBBINS
               <interp inst="t18270913-360-person2600" type="surname" value="GIBBINS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-360-person2600" type="given" value="FRANCIS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-360-person2600" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer. I saw a crowd of people at the corner of Long-lane, about a quarter-past eight o'clock in the evening of the 25th of July; a gentleman said, "I believe that child has been robbed of a bundle of linen;" I saw an ass and some hampers of apples there; I locked them up in the Green-yard, and by that means we got information of the prisoners.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270913-360-person2601">
                  HENRY 
                  SUMNER
               <interp inst="t18270913-360-person2601" type="surname" value="SUMNER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-360-person2601" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-360-person2601" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . On the 25th of July, about half-past seven o'clock in the evening, this little girl came for the bundle of linen; I gave it to her, and told her to take care of it.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270913-360-person2602">
                  JAMES 
                  VINT
               <interp inst="t18270913-360-person2602" type="surname" value="VINT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-360-person2602" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-360-person2602" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a constable. The ass and apples being taken to the Green-yard, I gave orders that no one should have them but the owner; and Mrs. Page, to whom the Green-yard belongs, came, and brought Donoghue to me; he said that he had run after the other boy - in the evening, Mrs. Page sent to me again, and said she had got Edwards; he said that the other had induced him to take the bundle, and before he took it, he had taken a handkerchief out of it; he said he had sold it in Petticoat-lane - I went there, but could hear nothing of it.</p>
               <p>EDWARDS' Defence. The things were on another man's head; he asked me to take them, which I did. When I got home my parents would not let me in - I went and sold them.</p>
               <p>DONOGHUE'S Defence. When I sent the little girl for the pipes, some man said this boy had taken the bundle; and he persuaded me to go after him - I said I would if any body would take care of the donkey; a gentleman said he would mind it; I went, but could not find him.</p>
               <p>DONOGHUE - <rs id="t18270913-360-verdict2002" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18270913-360-verdict2002" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 17.</p>

               <p>EDWARDS - <rs id="t18270913-360-verdict2003" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18270913-360-verdict2003" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 13.</p>
